<p><strong>Understanding the Z12XEP Engine: A Comprehensive Guide</strong></p>
<p><strong>Q: What is the Z12XEP engine?</strong></p>
<p><strong>A:</strong> The Z12XEP is a 1.2-liter gasoline engine developed by Opel, a subsidiary of General Motors. It is a four-cylinder, naturally aspirated engine with a displacement of 1199 cc. It was first introduced in 2004 and is commonly found in various Opel and Vauxhall models.</p>
<p><strong>Q: What are the specifications of the Z12XEP engine?</strong></p>
<p><strong>A:</strong> The Z12XEP engine produces 75 horsepower at 5600 rpm and 110 Nm of torque at 4000 rpm. It has a compression ratio of 10.5:1 and uses a single overhead camshaft (SOHC) with variable valve timing. The engine is known for its reliability and fuel efficiency.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Where is the Z12XEP engine used?</strong></p>
<p><strong>A:</strong> The Z12XEP engine was used in a wide range of Opel and Vauxhall models, including the Agila, Astra, Corsa, Meriva, and Tigra. It was also used in the Chevrolet Aveo and the Holden Barina.</p>
<p><strong>Q: What is the difference between the Z12XEP and Z14XEP engines?</strong></p>
<p><strong>A:</strong> The Z14XEP engine is a slightly larger version of the Z12XEP engine. It has a displacement of 1398 cc and produces more power and torque. The Z14XEP engine is also found in various Opel and Vauxhall models.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Where can I find more information about the Z12XEP engine?</strong></p>
<p><strong>A:</strong> Detailed information about the Z12XEP engine can be found in the engine's technical documentation. This documentation is often available online in PDF format. It provides specifications, maintenance guidelines, and troubleshooting tips.</p>